First what we need to do is obtain the number of screens that were considered bad. We then find the null and alternative hypothesis. The null would be H0: p = .005 an the alternative hypothesis would be HA: p >.005. Then we have to check if it passes the assumptions of whether the data was a random sample, whether the data was 10% less than the entire population and the success or failure condition (np > 10; and n(1-p)). We then state whether it will be distributed normally. Find the mean (which is the same as the null) and the standard deviation (sqrt of(( P0 (1-p0)/n)). Find the z statistic which is p-hat - p0 divided by the standard deviation. Find the p value from the z table an subtract than from one. If the value is smaller than alpha than reject the H0 and if it is bigger than alpha do not reject the H0. Create a conclusion see whether the 150 screens are bad.

1.  I would plot Mark's data on a histogram, and then plot Dan's data on another.  I would compare these 2 histograms to determine the shape and whether or not there are any outliers. /  / 2.  I would then locate the Maximum, Minimum, Median, 1st Quartile, and 23rd Quartile.  I would plot these points in the beginnings of a boxplot.  To determine how far the whiskers go I would add or subtract 1.5IQR from the Quartiles. /      Minimum<Q1-1.5IQR=> The whisker goes out to Q1-1.5IQR, with lower points denoted by dots. /      Minimum>Q1-1.5IQR=> The whisker goes out to the Minimum. /      Maximum<Q3+1.5IQR=> The whisker goes out to Q3+1.5IQR, with higher points denoted by dots. /      Maximum>Q3+1.5IQR=> The whisker goes out to the Maximum. /  / 3.  I would finally compare the 2 boxplots to each other, drawing a line in at the overall mean, which I found by calculating the average length of all the fish caught.  The boxplot that is higher than the overall mean, and has a smaller IQR and whiskers will be the better fisherman of the 2, because they catch larger fish, with a smaller variability in the lengths of fish they catch.
